    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, we'll check the scrap and rework logs to see if they align with these gaps. \n\nBut I'm still stuck on the \"nature\" of it. It feels almost... weirdly consistent. Like, it's never a big shipment, just these tiny handfuls of parts. Even when we're extra careful with the scanning, those single digits keep popping up. Is there any technical reason why electronic components specifically would have these kinds of \"phantom\" losses, or is it just always going to be these small, annoying gaps in the data?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's not just annoying gaps; sometimes, it's a technical quirk, though it's rarely as dramatic as a full-scale heist. When dealing with tiny electronic components, the sheer volume and the way they are packaged can cause issues that mimic vanishing stock.\n\nFor instance, if you are counting by case or reel, but the system is tracking by individual unit, there's a risk of *partial* counts being logged incorrectly. A reel might be partially used, and if the system doesn't perfectly account for the exact number of units taken from that reel, you get a small variance. It's the difference between counting a whole pile and counting every single grain of sand—a very fine-grained problem.\n\nAnother possibility, and this is more technical, is environmental or handling damage that isn't immediately obvious. Static discharge, for example, can sometimes render a component unusable, and if the receiving or picking staff just toss the damaged item aside without logging it as \"damaged/scrapped,\" it effectively disappears from the system count. It's the digital equivalent of a tiny, invisible pile of dust that the warehouse floor sweep just sweeps away.",
      "source": "target",
